<appendix xml:id="appendix-canoes">
<title>An Introduction to the Canoes in This Book</title>
<introduction>
    <p>
        Throughout this textbook, we reference several canoes that reflect the diverse traditions and practices of seafaring in the Pacific. Some of these canoes have traversed vast stretches of the ocean, while others are regional vessels that play vital roles in local education, cultural preservation, and community connection. In this appendix, we highlight each of these canoes to honor their contributions and emphasize the important role they play in sustaining ancestral knowledge and navigation practices.
    </p>
</introduction>
<section xml:id="sec-alingano-maisu">
    <title>Alingano Maisu</title>
    <p>
        The Alingano Maisu is a double-hulled voyaging canoe built in Kawaihae in 2007 by members of Na Kalai Waʻa Moku o Hawaiʻi as a gift to Mau Piailug and the people of Satawal. It is the sister canoe to Makaliʻi.
    </p>
    <image width="75%" source="canoe-alingano-maisu.jpg" />
</section>
<section xml:id="sec-faafaite">
    <title>Faʻafaite</title>
    <p>
        Faʻafaite is a double-hulled voyaging canoe built in 2009. It is one of eight vaka moana built for the Okeanos Foundation for the Sea. It is owned by the Faʻafaite - Tahiti Voyaging Society.
    </p>
    <image width="75%" source="canoe-faafaite.jpg" />
</section>
